--- a/ports/os/README.md
+++ b/ports/os/README.md
@@ -1,47 +1,39 @@
-# The minimal port
+# MicroPython port for OS userland
 
-This port is intended to be a minimal MicroPython port that actually runs.
-It can run under Linux (or similar) and on any STM32F4xx MCU (eg the pyboard).
+This minimal port builds a freestanding RV64 ELF executable for the kernel in
+this repository. It uses the kernel's user syscall ABI directly:
 
-## Building and running Linux version
+- `a0 = 0`, `a1 = status`: exit
+- `a0 = 1`, `a1 = buffer`, `a2 = length`: console write
+- `a0 = 2`, `a1 = buffer`, `a2 = length`: blocking console read
 
-By default the port will be built for the host machine:
+The kernel enters `_start` with a prepared user stack and zero-filled BSS. The
+port initializes `gp`, runs the standard friendly MicroPython REPL, and exits
+through syscall 0 when the REPL finishes.
 
-    $ make
+## Build
 
-To run the executable and get a basic working REPL do:
+Install Zig once; it supplies the RISC-V cross compiler and target headers, so
+no target-specific GCC toolchain is required:
 
-    $ make run
+```sh
+# macOS
+brew install zig
 
-## Building for an STM32 MCU
+make -C ports/os
+```
 
-The Makefile has the ability to build for a Cortex-M CPU, and by default
-includes some start-up code for an STM32F4xx MCU and also enables a UART
-for communication.  To build:
+Other platforms can use a binary from the official Zig download page. This
+port is tested with Zig 0.16.0.
 
-    $ make CROSS=1
+The OS userland build invokes this port through the same package interface as
+the other user programs and installs it as `/bin/micropython`:
 
-If you previously built the Linux version, you will need to first run
-`make clean` to get rid of incompatible object files.
+```sh
+make -C userland build
+```
 
-Building will produce the build/firmware.dfu file which can be programmed
-to an MCU using:
-
-    $ make CROSS=1 deploy
-
-This version of the build will work out-of-the-box on a pyboard (and
-anything similar), and will give you a MicroPython REPL on UART1 at 9600
-baud.  Pin PA13 will also be driven high, and this turns on the red LED on
-the pyboard.
-
-## Building without the built-in MicroPython compiler
-
-This minimal port can be built with the built-in MicroPython compiler
-disabled.  This will reduce the firmware by about 20k on a Thumb2 machine,
-and by about 40k on 32-bit x86.  Without the compiler the REPL will be
-disabled, but pre-compiled scripts can still be executed.
-
-To test out this feature, change the `MICROPY_ENABLE_COMPILER` config
-option to "0" in the mpconfigport.h file in this directory.  Then
-recompile and run the firmware and it will execute the frozentest.py
-file.
+The resulting stripped user executable is `ports/os/build/firmware.elf`.
+Install the ELF in the kernel's init archive and execute it with `kernel_exec`.
+Console input and output then use the same NS16550 console as the kernel, so
+the REPL is interactive on QEMU's `-nographic` terminal.
